# BUSINESS MODEL TO REPRESENT ON PAGE\
\
Use these ideas in the page structure and messaging:\
\
## Operational Reality\
- Scanning one aircraft\'92s records can take around 10 hours\
- Some jobs may take 2\'963 days depending on record volume\
- The work must be handled by someone who understands aircraft documents\
- Records include:\
  - airframe logbooks\
  - engine logbooks\
  - propeller records\
  - avionics records\
  - maintenance entries\
  - inspection records\
  - supporting aircraft documents\
\
## Professional Handling\
Position the service as being handled by trained aviation record specialists / A&P-aware professionals.\
Do not make reckless legal claims.\
Do not oversell certifications if not explicitly confirmed.\
Instead say things like:\
- \'93Handled by aviation-aware professionals\'94\
- \'93Organized with aircraft-record understanding\'94\
- \'93Structured to match real-world maintenance documentation categories\'94\
\
## Pricing Direction\
Represent two commercial options:\
\
### Option A \'97 One-Time Scan Job\
Example positioning:\
- \'93Request a one-time aircraft records scanning job\'94\
- \'93Ideal for owners, schools, fleet operators, brokers, and prebuy preparation\'94\
\
### Option B \'97 Subscription-Based Recovery Model\
Example positioning:\
- Spread scan/setup cost across a recurring plan\
- Lower upfront cost\
- Monthly structure around approximately $27/month over 36 months as a sample concept\
- If the user cancels early, remaining scanning/setup balance may become due\
- This should be described as a business option, not locked legal language unless contract text exists\
\
IMPORTANT:\
Do not present unfinished pricing as final law.\
Use wording like:\
- \'93Example subscription structure\'94\
- \'93Custom quotes available\'94\
- \'93Terms subject to agreement\'94\
